Question 1

Flowchart for gcd():
Pseudocode for gcd():
IF(the input is not a positive integer)
    STOP and give an error message

IF(a is less than b)
    SWAP a and b so that a is greater than or equal to b
  
REPEAT
    Create remainder variable, which is the remainder of a/b
    IF(remainder equals 0)
        Create greatest common divisor variable, assign b to it
    ELSE
        Assign b to a
        Assign the remainder variable to b
    
    IF(remainder equals zero)
        BREAK the repeat loop
  
RETURN the gcd variable
Flowchart for gcd_3():
Pseudocode for gcd_3():
RETURN gcd of gcd(a,b) and c using previous gcd function.
Test Cases for gcd():

## Error in gcd(4.5, 12) : Please enter positive integer values.
try(gcd(-1, 12))
## Error in gcd(-1, 12) : Please enter positive integer values.

Question 2

Flowchart for is_prime():
Pseudocode for is_prime():
Create logical vector called primes with length equal to length of input vector.

FOR(i in 1 to length of x)
    IF(x[i] is not an integer greater than 1)
        Assign FALSE to primes[i]
    ELSE IF(x[i] is 2)
        Assign TRUE to primes[i]
    ELSE IF(x[i] mod every number from 2 to
            the square root of x[i] rounded up is not 0)
        Assign TRUE to primes[i]
    ELSE
        Assign FALSE to primes[i]
      
RETURN primes vector
Flowchart for get_factors():
Pseudocode for get_factors():
IF(the input is not a positive integer greater than 1)
    STOP and give an error message
    
Create empty numeric vector named factors

FOR(i in 2 to x)
    FOR(n in 0 to 1023)
        IF((x / i^n) mod i is zero)
            Append i to the end of the factors vector
        ELSE
            BREAK out of the inside loop
            
Create logical vector named primes of length of factors

FOR(i in 1 to the length of factors)
    Assign is_prime(i-th element of factors) to i-th element of primes
    
RETURN factors[primes], which is only the prime factors
Test cases for is_prime():

## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
